Cicero's defense of old age is so charming in style and so interesting in matter that it deserves something more by way of commentary than mere discussion of gram- matical and linguistic usage. Accordingly an attempt has been made in the illustrative notes, on the pages with the text, to give prominence to the historical and literary features of the essay, and to show by numerous quotations what ancient and modern authors have uttered like thoughtS, couched in similar forms of expression.

In order that the chief emphasis may be placed on the literary element, the grammatical and textual commentary is placed in a separate body of notes following the text. The commentarios are supplemented bya list of variations from the text of Muller, an index to the notes and an index of proper names.
